## Overview

This repository documents an end-to-end **patch and vulnerability management program** for a production fleet of Linux servers, network appliances, storage systems, and hypervisors supporting business-critical healthcare workloads.

It pairs a **risk-based remediation policy** — severity tiers, SLAs, and approval gates — with the **hands-on runbooks** used to deliver it: centralized Linux patching through Oracle Spacewalk (Oracle Linux Manager), vulnerability prioritization via Tenable, and a multi-environment promotion pipeline that moves patches safely from development to production.

The intent is to show the *whole shape* of the work — not just running `yum update`, but how patches are screened, prioritized, tested, scheduled, approved, and tied back to audit controls.

## What this demonstrates

- **Centralized Linux patch management** with Oracle Spacewalk — channel design, ULN / public-yum repo syncing, activation keys, and emergency channels for out-of-cycle critical fixes.
- **Risk-based vulnerability management** — translating Tenable VPR scores into severity tiers and remediation SLAs.
- **Change-controlled promotion** — Dev → Pre-Prod → Production (secondary site → primary site) with sociability-testing gates.
- **Heterogeneous fleet operations** — documented procedures spanning Cisco, NetApp, FortiGate, Infoblox, F5, VMware, Oracle ZS3/firmware, and more.
- **Compliance alignment** — process mapped to SOC 2, ISO 27001, and HIPAA expectations.
- **Operational engineering** — certificate/SSL import, NFS-backed package stores, and real-world troubleshooting (e.g. jabberd database recovery).

## Centralized patching architecture

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    ULN[Unbreakable Linux Network] --> SW
    OYUM[Oracle Public Yum] --> SW
    subgraph SW[Oracle Spacewalk / Linux Manager]
        PC[Parent channels] --> CC[Child channels + errata]
    end
    CC -->|activation keys| DEV[Dev environment]
    CC --> PPS[Pre-Prod / PPS]
    CC --> P2[Production - secondary site]
    CC --> P1[Production - primary site]
    EMG[[Emergency channel]] -. critical out-of-cycle .-> P1
```

Repo syncing is **paused at the start of each cycle** so every environment is patched from an identical, frozen package set — guaranteeing version consistency from test through production.

## Risk-based prioritization

Vulnerabilities are scored with Tenable's **VPR (Vulnerability Priority Rating)** and mapped to internal severity tiers:

| VPR score | Internal severity |
|-----------|-------------------|
| ≥ 9.0     | Critical          |
| 8.0 – 8.9 | High              |
| ≤ 7.9     | Medium / Low      |

## Remediation SLA matrix

Time-to-patch (in days) by asset exposure and severity:

| Severity | Internet-facing | App / DB / Interfacing | Other Prod | Dev / Office |
|----------|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|
| **Critical** (VPR ≥ 9) | 7 | 14 | 21 | 21 |
| **High** (VPR 8–8.9)   | 14 | 21 | 28 | 30 |
| **Medium / Low** (VPR ≤ 7.9) | Standard quarterly cycle | | | |

The baseline cadence is a **quarterly cycle** aligned to Oracle's Critical Patch Updates (CPUs); critical and emergency fixes are pulled forward through a separate approval and deployment path.

## Patch lifecycle

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Quarterly cycle / CPU release] --> B[Tenable screening + VPR scoring]
    B --> C{Severity?}
    C -->|Critical / Emergency| D[Senior-mgmt risk assessment + approval]
    C -->|Standard| E[Freeze repo sync]
    D --> E
    E --> F[Deploy to Dev — ~2 wks sociability testing]
    F --> G[Deploy to Pre-Prod — ~2 wks validation]
    G --> H[Production secondary site]
    H --> I[Site cutover]
    I --> J[Production primary site]
```

